1
00:02:08,639 --> 00:02:10,520
- I'm here, Pie!
- Mom!

2
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:13,160
I missed you so much.

3
00:02:15,920 --> 00:02:17,520
<i>If she's happy,</i>

4
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:19,080
I'm okay with that.

5
00:02:19,160 --> 00:02:20,560
And what if she's not happy?

6
00:02:21,280 --> 00:02:22,880
When is your next ovulation?

7
00:02:22,960 --> 00:02:25,560
Bring me your schedule, so we can plan it.

8
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:27,680
I think we're already way behind schedule.

9
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:30,200
Pie will quit her job
to prepare for having a baby.

10
00:02:30,280 --> 00:02:31,640
No problem, right?

11
00:02:32,960 --> 00:02:34,560
You're joking, right?

12
00:02:35,160 --> 00:02:36,240
I'm serious.

13
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:39,920
You're at the best and safest age
to have a baby right now.

14
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:44,160
I made all these decisions for our family.

15
00:02:51,520 --> 00:02:54,360
I'm resigning at the end of this month,
right after your exams.

16
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,920
So that means we won't get to study
with you next year?

17
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:01,120
That's such a shame.

18
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:04,360
You're the only professor
whose class doesn't put me to sleep.

19
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:07,760
Can I ask where you'll be teaching
after you resign?

20
00:03:07,840 --> 00:03:10,560
The three of us can follow you there.

21
00:03:11,160 --> 00:03:12,800
I'm not resigning to teach somewhere else.

22
00:03:14,040 --> 00:03:15,720
I'm quitting to have a baby.

23
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:17,280
My husband wants me to stop working.

24
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:20,520
So jealous.

25
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:22,720
Jealous of what?

26
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:25,640
Your husband wants you
to quit and have a baby.

27
00:03:25,720 --> 00:03:28,760
You don't have to work,
and he still gives you money to spend.

28
00:03:28,840 --> 00:03:31,080
That's basically my dream life, Professor.

29
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:35,560
Having someone take care of you
isn't as comfortable as you think.

30
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:37,600
I like working and earning my own money.

31
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:41,600
It makes me feel
like my life still has value.

32
00:03:42,160 --> 00:03:44,480
Better than having to depend
on someone all the time.

33
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:48,880
Work also reminds me

34
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:51,560
that my life still belongs to me.

35
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:55,280
But now it doesn't anymore.

36
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:04,920
<i>Patience</i>
<i>and being willing to change yourself</i>

37
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:06,440
<i>are important in a relationship.</i>

38
00:04:06,520 --> 00:04:08,840
<i>But they're not always the answer.</i>

39
00:04:09,720 --> 00:04:12,520
<i>When two imperfect people</i>
<i>choose to build a life together,</i>

40
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:14,640
<i>all kinds of problems can come up.</i>

41
00:04:15,320 --> 00:04:19,480
<i>And without patience,</i>
<i>the relationship can fall apart.</i>

42
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:26,680
<i>I've been patient too, Pek,</i>
<i>but it's miserable as hell.</i>

43
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:30,800
<i>So miserable that I keep asking myself,</i>
<i>"Why the hell am I putting up with this?"</i>

44
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:31,960
I SAY IT LIKE THIS

45
00:04:32,040 --> 00:04:36,320
<i>Exactly. That's why I said patience</i>
<i>has to come with understanding too.</i>

46
00:04:36,880 --> 00:04:40,640
<i>You need to come to an agreement</i>
<i>with your partner and with yourself,</i>

47
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:43,000
<i>that that you're enduring it</i>
<i>so things can get better.</i>

48
00:04:44,280 --> 00:04:47,680
<i>Not just putting up with it,</i>
<i>giving in every time.</i>

49
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:51,840
<i>Keeping it all inside, not talking it out,</i>
<i>just letting it slide,</i>

50
00:04:51,920 --> 00:04:55,400
<i>without even knowing</i>
<i>why you're putting up with it.</i>

51
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:57,280
<i>That lack of understanding,</i>

52
00:04:57,360 --> 00:05:00,880
<i>it builds up more and more over time,</i>

53
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:03,200
<i>until it turns into a ticking time bomb.</i>

54
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:05,640
<i>Tick, tick, tick.</i>

55
00:05:05,720 --> 00:05:08,120
<i>And once your patience runs out…</i>

56
00:05:08,200 --> 00:05:10,360
<i>Boom! It all falls apart.</i>

57
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:11,600
I SAY IT LIKE THIS

58
00:05:11,680 --> 00:05:13,600
<i>I say it like this.</i>

59
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:16,760
<i>Patience and sacrifice are good things,</i>

60
00:05:16,840 --> 00:05:20,920
<i>but there has to be a middle ground.</i>
<i>Find that, and you'll find peace.</i>

61
00:05:21,760 --> 00:05:23,000
<i>Try looking for it.</i>

62
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:34,760
Now that we've looked
at all the other rooms,

63
00:05:34,840 --> 00:05:36,920
there's one important room left.

64
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:38,680
Our own office.

65
00:05:42,480 --> 00:05:44,360
Are the other employees out working?

66
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:48,080
Nope. It's just me and you two
in the office.

67
00:05:50,040 --> 00:05:52,760
If you count Phupha and Pun too,
that makes five of us total.

68
00:05:52,840 --> 00:05:55,280
As for everyone else,
we outsource them all.

69
00:05:55,360 --> 00:05:58,120
The office shut down during COVID,
so everything slowed down.

70
00:05:58,200 --> 00:06:00,160
We've just recovered and started
taking on new projects again,

71
00:06:00,240 --> 00:06:01,760
so that's why we need new staff.

72
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:04,280
Which is you two, exactly.

73
00:06:05,840 --> 00:06:07,760
Guys, Pun's here!

74
00:06:08,640 --> 00:06:09,880
Say hello to him.

75
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:12,000
- Hello.
- Hello.

76
00:06:12,080 --> 00:06:13,560
- Hello.
- Pun.

77
00:06:13,640 --> 00:06:15,240
This is Lukmai, our new architect,

78
00:06:15,320 --> 00:06:17,240
and Bae, our new graphic designer.

79
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:20,240
Welcome.

80
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,320
You don't need to stress working here.

81
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:25,640
I'm an easygoing guy.

82
00:06:28,720 --> 00:06:30,160
But

83
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:32,280
I don't like people who lack discipline.

84
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:34,840
Don't be late. Work is work, play is play.

85
00:06:34,920 --> 00:06:36,360
Don't use your phone at work.

86
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:38,520
Don't use the company computer
for social media.

87
00:06:38,600 --> 00:06:41,200
No farming games either.
I don't like seeing food on desks.

88
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:42,960
If you're hungry, use the dining room.

89
00:06:43,040 --> 00:06:44,520
Keep things clean, organized, and nice.

90
00:06:44,600 --> 00:06:46,000
That's all. Simple, right?

91
00:06:46,600 --> 00:06:47,440
- Yes.
- Yes.

92
00:06:47,520 --> 00:06:49,320
Because we're like family here.

93
00:06:49,400 --> 00:06:50,920
Easygoing. Relaxed.

94
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:53,600
Yes. Easygoing.

95
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:54,480
Got it, everyone?

96
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:57,640
Just like Pun said, easygoing and relaxed.

97
00:07:06,880 --> 00:07:10,160
Dinner at my mom's place tonight.
Don't be late, Pie.

98
00:07:21,520 --> 00:07:22,800
That was fast.

99
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:25,960
<i>Hey, Pun. It's me, Koh.</i>

100
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:29,800
Koh!

101
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:46,840
Pun.

102
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:50,080
Koh!

103
00:07:55,320 --> 00:07:56,960
You look like a proper human being now.

104
00:07:58,120 --> 00:07:59,280
Was that a compliment or an insult?

105
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:04,040
A compliment. Come on. Time to get drunk.

106
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:05,000
Let's drink.

107
00:08:14,320 --> 00:08:15,200
PUN

108
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:17,200
Yes, Pun?

109
00:08:17,720 --> 00:08:20,040
You don't need to go to my mom's
for dinner tonight.

110
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:23,000
A close junior friend of mine
just got back from Japan.

111
00:08:23,080 --> 00:08:26,120
<i>We haven't seen each other in a long time,</i>
<i>so I'm taking him out to eat.</i>

112
00:08:26,200 --> 00:08:29,240
I already told my mom
we're canceling too. Is that okay?

113
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:31,680
That's fine, Pun. Don't worry about me.

114
00:08:31,760 --> 00:08:33,799
I'll just grab
something simple around here.

115
00:08:33,880 --> 00:08:35,440
I'll be home late tonight.

116
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:38,080
<i>No problem at all, Pun. Enjoy yourself.</i>

117
00:08:38,640 --> 00:08:39,480
Okay.

118
00:08:41,480 --> 00:08:44,960
No dinner at Mom's. Freedom, yay!

119
00:08:50,280 --> 00:08:52,760
What should I eat?

120
00:08:52,840 --> 00:08:53,800
FRIED CHICKEN, GRILLED PORK, PAD KRA PAO

121
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:56,920
Fried chicken, burgers, fries, pizza…

122
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,520
I can't decide.

123
00:08:59,480 --> 00:09:01,160
Guess I'm having it all.

124
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:07,120
That smile means your wife's not mad, huh?

125
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:09,280
My wife's never mad at me.

126
00:09:09,360 --> 00:09:11,280
If there's anything, we talk it out.

127
00:09:12,520 --> 00:09:14,000
I'll introduce you to her sometime.

128
00:09:14,680 --> 00:09:17,360
But tonight, no wives allowed.

129
00:09:18,560 --> 00:09:20,360
It's just sworn brothers tonight.

130
00:09:21,480 --> 00:09:24,760
So, give me an update.
How was Japan for you?

131
00:09:25,360 --> 00:09:26,600
Have a drink first, Pun.

132
00:09:27,240 --> 00:09:29,280
You never change.

133
00:09:32,760 --> 00:09:33,760
Nice.

134
00:09:34,880 --> 00:09:37,280
You still drink with peanuts, huh?

135
00:09:37,360 --> 00:09:39,600
You won't touch any other bar snacks.
Still a health freak.

136
00:09:39,680 --> 00:09:41,640
You are what you eat.

137
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:43,960
You only get one life, so take care of it.

138
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:50,280
I haven't had a drink in a long time,
but today's a special occasion.

139
00:09:51,800 --> 00:09:52,800
Come on.

140
00:09:52,880 --> 00:09:55,440
Are you gonna tell me or not?
How was Japan?

141
00:09:56,360 --> 00:09:57,880
Nothing much, really.

142
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:02,080
It was hard, but it was worth it.

143
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:05,040
Here.

144
00:10:06,040 --> 00:10:08,960
I saved up and brought back
every last penny I owe you.

145
00:10:09,040 --> 00:10:09,880
Take it.

146
00:10:10,720 --> 00:10:12,640
No. I gave it to you.

147
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:15,080
You don't have to pay me back. Keep it.

148
00:10:15,160 --> 00:10:18,120
- No, Pun. Take it. You helped me so much.
- Hey.

149
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:19,400
If you won't take it,

150
00:10:19,480 --> 00:10:21,760
I'll spend this money
on booze right now. Want that?

151
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:22,720
You little punk.

152
00:10:24,240 --> 00:10:25,360
Just take it, Pun.

153
00:10:25,960 --> 00:10:27,200
I mean it.

154
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:29,320
Don't worry.

155
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:30,880
I'm only repaying the money.

156
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:33,280
I still owe you for the rest.

157
00:10:33,360 --> 00:10:36,240
What you did for me
was worth more than money.

158
00:10:41,480 --> 00:10:42,480
Alright.

159
00:10:44,040 --> 00:10:45,320
Then I'll take it.

160
00:10:49,680 --> 00:10:51,400
I'm really proud of you.

161
00:10:54,120 --> 00:10:55,120
Finish your glass, Pun.

162
00:10:56,640 --> 00:10:57,640
Sure.

163
00:11:00,200 --> 00:11:01,720
It's been a while, so drink up.

164
00:11:08,600 --> 00:11:11,720
That's not like you. Finish it, Pun.

165
00:11:11,800 --> 00:11:13,240
Same old me. Don't you remember?

166
00:11:13,320 --> 00:11:15,560
Yeah, exactly the same.
Bottoms up. Come on.

167
00:11:15,640 --> 00:11:16,760
Drink up!

168
00:11:16,840 --> 00:11:17,840
Come on!

169
00:11:18,440 --> 00:11:19,920
Drink!

170
00:11:20,560 --> 00:11:21,960
- Tian.
- Yes, ma'am?

171
00:11:22,040 --> 00:11:23,160
Are they back yet?

172
00:11:23,240 --> 00:11:25,840
Yes, ma'am.
But only one of them came back.

173
00:11:25,920 --> 00:11:26,960
Really?

174
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:29,440
- Come with me.
- Yes, ma'am.

175
00:11:29,520 --> 00:11:30,760
Where are you going?

176
00:11:33,320 --> 00:11:34,800
I'm going over to check on that house.

177
00:11:35,520 --> 00:11:38,440
Pun went out for dinner,
and Pie's home alone.

178
00:11:38,520 --> 00:11:39,640
Why do you need to check on her?

179
00:11:40,560 --> 00:11:42,360
I'm going to make sure
everything's in order.

180
00:11:43,080 --> 00:11:47,000
I want to see what his wife does
when Pun isn't home.

181
00:11:47,080 --> 00:11:49,800
Isn't that a bit much? Just let it go.

182
00:11:49,880 --> 00:11:52,840
If Pun had chosen
someone a little more proper,

183
00:11:52,920 --> 00:11:54,880
I wouldn't have to be like this.

184
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,480
Who knows what he picked up.

185
00:11:57,200 --> 00:11:58,800
How am I supposed to let it go?

186
00:11:59,400 --> 00:12:00,720
- Come on, Tian.
- Yes, ma'am.

187
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:12,400
If I hadn't had you back then,

188
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:14,960
my life would've been completely wrecked.

189
00:12:16,840 --> 00:12:19,880
And I'm sorry that I never reached out.

190
00:12:20,760 --> 00:12:23,160
I stayed off social media.
Didn't want distractions.

191
00:12:23,240 --> 00:12:25,360
I only focused on studying and work.

192
00:12:25,960 --> 00:12:27,360
Hey, don't overthink it.

193
00:12:28,360 --> 00:12:31,120
Just seeing you have hope again,

194
00:12:31,200 --> 00:12:32,680
with a goal in life,

195
00:12:33,200 --> 00:12:34,240
I'm already happy.

196
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:36,960
Pun, don't make it emotional.

197
00:12:37,040 --> 00:12:38,600
We're guys. Come on.

198
00:12:39,280 --> 00:12:41,240
If I start crying in a bar,
that'd be embarrassing.

199
00:12:42,040 --> 00:12:44,000
You're so dramatic.

200
00:12:46,920 --> 00:12:48,920
But your timing is actually perfect.

201
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:50,760
I'm looking for someone to help with work.

202
00:12:50,840 --> 00:12:53,320
Pun, you seriously know me so well.

203
00:12:53,880 --> 00:12:55,360
I was about to ask you for a job.

204
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:57,400
No need to ask.
I already have a job for you.

205
00:12:58,200 --> 00:13:01,240
Finding a museum designer
I actually like is really hard.

206
00:13:01,320 --> 00:13:02,840
Bring me your portfolio.

207
00:13:02,920 --> 00:13:05,560
Don't worry. I've got it ready.
I'll send it to you right away.

208
00:13:05,640 --> 00:13:07,480
- Good.
- How about we celebrate in advance

209
00:13:07,560 --> 00:13:09,960
for getting to work together?

210
00:13:10,920 --> 00:13:12,240
Welcome aboard.

211
00:13:12,320 --> 00:13:14,720
- My little bro.
- Yeah. Bottoms up.

212
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:17,040
- Bottoms up again.
- Let's go.

213
00:13:20,720 --> 00:13:24,160
Pun! Pun! Pun!

214
00:13:38,720 --> 00:13:40,280
Have you resigned yet?

215
00:13:43,160 --> 00:13:44,200
Yes, I have.

216
00:13:46,600 --> 00:13:48,160
Then you can start prepping for a baby.

217
00:13:51,040 --> 00:13:52,920
Why are you eating food like this?

218
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:54,520
Aren't you thinking about the baby?

219
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:56,640
Mom, but I'm not pregnant yet.

220
00:13:56,720 --> 00:13:59,600
You may not be pregnant now,
but it's still your body.

221
00:14:00,840 --> 00:14:03,520
If you don't take care of it,
how will it be prepared for pregnancy?

222
00:14:04,640 --> 00:14:07,920
You need to prepare your body,
your womb, for my grandchild.

223
00:14:08,680 --> 00:14:10,120
Stop eating this kind of food.

224
00:14:10,200 --> 00:14:12,920
I don't want my grandchild
picking up your habit of eating anything.

225
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:18,280
- Tian.
- Yes, ma'am.

226
00:14:22,200 --> 00:14:24,360
Aunt Tian, but I'm still eating that.

227
00:14:24,960 --> 00:14:27,160
I'll bring you proper food from our house.

228
00:14:27,800 --> 00:14:29,240
Learn to choose what you eat.

229
00:14:29,320 --> 00:14:30,400
You are what you eat.

230
00:14:30,480 --> 00:14:31,400
Remember that.

231
00:14:35,040 --> 00:14:38,200
And stop doing things
behind your husband's back

232
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:40,480
when he's not home.

233
00:14:40,560 --> 00:14:41,720
Remember,

234
00:14:42,560 --> 00:14:44,080
there are no secrets in this world.

235
00:15:07,880 --> 00:15:09,240
Koh.

236
00:15:10,760 --> 00:15:11,720
Koh.

237
00:15:12,760 --> 00:15:13,920
Koh!

238
00:15:14,600 --> 00:15:15,520
Hey!

239
00:15:19,640 --> 00:15:21,360
You passed out already?

240
00:15:23,920 --> 00:15:26,560
How am I supposed
to carry you home like this?

241
00:15:34,560 --> 00:15:35,800
Koh.

242
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:38,480
You're heavy as hell.

243
00:15:44,720 --> 00:15:46,160
What have you been eating?

244
00:15:48,440 --> 00:15:50,040
Koh.

245
00:15:55,640 --> 00:15:57,440
You're seriously so heavy.

246
00:15:59,920 --> 00:16:01,400
Sleeping so well, idiot?

247
00:16:52,040 --> 00:16:53,040
Pie.

248
00:16:54,440 --> 00:16:55,320
Pie.

249
00:16:58,840 --> 00:16:59,800
Pun?

250
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:03,080
What time is it?

251
00:17:03,800 --> 00:17:05,520
Did you order fried chicken?

252
00:17:07,160 --> 00:17:09,640
I told you not to eat junk food.
It's not good for you.

253
00:17:09,720 --> 00:17:11,839
And no soda either. It's too sweet.

254
00:17:13,079 --> 00:17:14,880
It's fine once in a while, right?

255
00:17:14,960 --> 00:17:16,760
It's not fine,
even if it's once in a while.

256
00:17:16,839 --> 00:17:17,800
And the TV.

257
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:20,760
How many times
have I told you not to leave it on?

258
00:17:20,839 --> 00:17:23,119
It emits blue light,
which messes with your sleep.

259
00:17:24,480 --> 00:17:27,119
But I slept just fine earlier.
I didn't notice anything.

260
00:17:27,200 --> 00:17:28,680
Until you woke me up to yell at me.

261
00:17:33,040 --> 00:17:35,640
Pun, it's 3 a.m.

262
00:17:35,720 --> 00:17:37,560
Do you have to wake me up
and yell at me now?

263
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:40,520
Pie.

264
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:43,880
Pie.

265
00:17:44,840 --> 00:17:46,560
I'm just worried about you.

266
00:17:47,080 --> 00:17:51,120
And remember, we agreed
that you'd take care of your health.

267
00:17:51,200 --> 00:17:53,040
You'd get enough rest.

268
00:17:53,120 --> 00:17:54,800
You'd eat better for the baby.

269
00:17:55,320 --> 00:17:57,160
Not junk food like this.

270
00:17:59,600 --> 00:18:00,520
Pun.

271
00:18:01,160 --> 00:18:04,200
The baby's not eating junk food,
because the baby's not here yet.

272
00:18:04,280 --> 00:18:06,800
And the baby's mom
hasn't been getting enough sleep either.

273
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:08,400
But it's not because of blue light.

274
00:18:08,480 --> 00:18:10,040
It's because the dad woke me up.

275
00:18:11,880 --> 00:18:14,480
If you didn't do this, I wouldn't have
to wake you up and complain.

276
00:18:17,160 --> 00:18:18,920
I don't want to argue with you.

277
00:18:20,360 --> 00:18:21,600
I just want to remind you.

278
00:18:23,240 --> 00:18:24,440
Out of concern.

279
00:20:42,160 --> 00:20:43,160
Get out!

280
00:20:43,240 --> 00:20:45,400
Get out now! Out!

281
00:20:45,480 --> 00:20:47,280
Hey, wait a second!

282
00:20:47,360 --> 00:20:48,800
Get out of my house right now!

283
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,800
- Get out! How did you get in here?
- Hey, wait!

284
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:54,240
- I said, get out!
- Wait a second!

285
00:20:54,320 --> 00:20:56,920
- Get out of my house! Out!
- Hold on!

286
00:20:57,000 --> 00:20:59,480
- Get out now!
- Hold on!

287
00:20:59,560 --> 00:21:01,400
- Get out!
- Wait a second!

288
00:21:01,480 --> 00:21:03,200
- Get out!
- Calm down!

289
00:21:03,280 --> 00:21:05,680
- That's enough. Stop!
- I said, get out!

290
00:21:10,120 --> 00:21:10,960
Pie.

291
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:14,240
Calm down. This is my friend.

292
00:21:32,800 --> 00:21:33,720
Pie?

293
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:38,480
Friend?

294
00:21:45,440 --> 00:21:46,440
Your friend?

295
00:21:48,520 --> 00:21:49,800
Yes.

296
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:53,160
This is the friend I told you about.

297
00:21:53,240 --> 00:21:55,000
The one I was going to introduce you to.

298
00:21:56,240 --> 00:21:57,840
This is him. I haven't seen him in ages.

299
00:21:57,920 --> 00:21:59,080
He just returned from Japan.

300
00:22:04,800 --> 00:22:05,760
This is Pie.

301
00:22:07,560 --> 00:22:08,840
Yes, Pie.

302
00:22:08,920 --> 00:22:11,240
And she is my wife.

303
00:22:14,200 --> 00:22:15,160
Your wife?

304
00:22:27,760 --> 00:22:29,920
Hey, Koh.

305
00:22:30,920 --> 00:22:33,520
Koh, you okay?

306
00:22:34,200 --> 00:22:36,080
I told you not to drink too much.

307
00:22:37,480 --> 00:22:38,480
I'm fine, Pun.

308
00:22:47,240 --> 00:22:48,200
Sorry.

309
00:22:48,800 --> 00:22:53,320
Well, I didn't tell Pie
that you were coming to stay over.

310
00:22:53,960 --> 00:22:55,160
That's why she was shocked.

311
00:22:58,960 --> 00:23:01,360
Yes, because he's your friend.

312
00:23:02,080 --> 00:23:03,400
Not mine.

313
00:23:10,760 --> 00:23:12,160
Wait for me here, Koh.

314
00:23:13,680 --> 00:23:14,840
Pie.

315
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:17,280
Pie.

316
00:23:28,520 --> 00:23:29,520
Pie.

317
00:23:30,400 --> 00:23:31,280
Pie.

318
00:23:32,720 --> 00:23:33,600
Pie.

319
00:23:37,240 --> 00:23:38,520
I'm sorry.

320
00:23:39,240 --> 00:23:41,120
I was planning to tell you tomorrow.

321
00:23:41,200 --> 00:23:43,920
Koh got drunk, so I brought him here.
It's no big deal.

322
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:46,960
No. I don't want him staying here.

323
00:23:47,040 --> 00:23:48,560
You need to take him out right now.

324
00:23:48,640 --> 00:23:49,960
What?

325
00:23:50,040 --> 00:23:53,480
Pie, it's 4 a.m.
Can't we wait until morning?

326
00:23:53,560 --> 00:23:56,080
No. He has to go now.

327
00:25:11,840 --> 00:25:12,880
Pie.

328
00:25:13,520 --> 00:25:15,320
Can you be reasonable?

329
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:18,440
Having a friend stay over
isn't a big deal.

330
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:21,400
And Koh is trustworthy.

331
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:23,560
I've known him since we were kids.

332
00:25:23,640 --> 00:25:25,840
I've known him longer than I've known you.

333
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:38,480
I'm sorry I didn't tell you beforehand.

334
00:25:39,280 --> 00:25:40,640
I admit I was wrong.

335
00:25:40,720 --> 00:25:43,760
But I don't see any reason
to make him leave.

336
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:51,600
I think I made a mistake

337
00:25:53,640 --> 00:25:55,480
waking you up in the middle of the night,

338
00:25:55,560 --> 00:25:56,800
which is why you're upset.

339
00:26:01,760 --> 00:26:03,200
Just go back to bed.

340
00:26:05,200 --> 00:26:07,680
In the morning,
when you wake up in a better mood,

341
00:26:08,480 --> 00:26:11,200
you'll see it's really not a big deal.

342
00:26:14,840 --> 00:26:16,600
Please, just go back to sleep.

343
00:26:21,920 --> 00:26:22,880
Okay?

344
00:27:23,520 --> 00:27:26,240
Hey, Koh, sorry about that.

345
00:27:32,760 --> 00:27:33,680
Are you okay?

346
00:27:37,160 --> 00:27:39,120
Pie was just a bit shocked earlier.

347
00:27:39,960 --> 00:27:41,840
Go sleep in the guest room instead.

348
00:27:41,920 --> 00:27:45,120
In the morning,
I'll introduce you to Pie properly.

349
00:27:45,840 --> 00:27:46,720
Go ahead.

350
00:27:48,480 --> 00:27:51,400
It's fine, Pun. I think
I'll head back to the hotel.

351
00:27:53,400 --> 00:27:55,160
Why go back? Stay here.

352
00:27:55,240 --> 00:27:57,720
You can stay. Don't worry about it.

353
00:27:58,320 --> 00:28:00,760
I've already troubled you enough.

354
00:28:00,840 --> 00:28:02,120
I think I should go back.

355
00:28:03,240 --> 00:28:04,760
I've already called a ride.

356
00:28:05,640 --> 00:28:07,200
It's almost here.

357
00:28:14,520 --> 00:28:15,680
It's up to you then.

358
00:28:15,760 --> 00:28:16,920
You sure you're okay?

359
00:28:18,600 --> 00:28:19,560
Let me walk you out.

360
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:36,880
<i>This is Pie.</i>

361
00:29:37,520 --> 00:29:41,240
<i>Yes, Pie. And she is my wife.</i>

362
00:30:09,880 --> 00:30:11,320
<i>I love you the most, Pie!</i>

363
00:30:11,400 --> 00:30:14,040
<i>I love you the most, Win!</i>

364
00:31:27,040 --> 00:31:28,360
How are you doing?

365
00:31:28,440 --> 00:31:30,040
Are you less upset about last night?

366
00:31:33,160 --> 00:31:36,720
See, I told you it wasn't a big deal.

367
00:31:44,120 --> 00:31:45,960
- Pun.
- Yes?

368
00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:51,440
You said you've known this friend
since you were a kid?

369
00:31:52,720 --> 00:31:55,840
Actually, I've known him since birth.

370
00:31:55,920 --> 00:31:56,840
His name is Koh.

371
00:31:58,600 --> 00:32:00,880
- Koh?
- Yeah.

372
00:32:00,960 --> 00:32:03,080
His house was right across from ours.

373
00:32:03,800 --> 00:32:06,200
My parents were really close
with his parents.

374
00:32:06,280 --> 00:32:09,120
Both families only had one son,

375
00:32:09,200 --> 00:32:10,560
so they raised us like siblings.

376
00:32:11,160 --> 00:32:13,080
I'm the one who gave him the name Koh.

377
00:32:13,160 --> 00:32:15,880
When we were kids,
we were always together, like Pa Tong Koh.

378
00:32:15,960 --> 00:32:17,560
I started calling him Koh.

379
00:32:17,640 --> 00:32:18,760
His real name is Win.

380
00:32:21,800 --> 00:32:25,400
So, he used to live across from us.

381
00:32:25,480 --> 00:32:26,880
When did he move?

382
00:32:29,080 --> 00:32:31,720
Well, just a few years ago.

383
00:32:32,720 --> 00:32:34,960
His life has been pretty sad, you know.

384
00:32:35,040 --> 00:32:38,920
His parents passed away
and left him with a huge debt.

385
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:40,240
His house was seized.

386
00:32:41,320 --> 00:32:43,120
He was so shocked, his life fell apart.

387
00:32:43,200 --> 00:32:45,200
He couldn't do anything, couldn't work.

388
00:32:45,280 --> 00:32:47,520
He just drank all the time.

389
00:32:47,600 --> 00:32:50,480
So, I sent him to live
with his aunt in Mae Hong Son.

390
00:32:51,560 --> 00:32:53,760
But he's still talented and lucky too.

391
00:32:54,280 --> 00:32:56,080
He got a scholarship to study in Japan.

392
00:32:57,360 --> 00:33:00,760
That's around when I stopped
keeping in touch with him.

393
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:06,360
Pie, honestly,

394
00:33:06,920 --> 00:33:10,000
I think if you met Koh
when he's sober and not shocked,

395
00:33:10,680 --> 00:33:12,040
I'm sure you'd like him.

396
00:33:17,160 --> 00:33:19,200
I'm serious, Pie.

397
00:33:19,880 --> 00:33:21,240
You'd be okay with him.

398
00:33:21,320 --> 00:33:25,240
He's harmless. He's just funny,
a bit clueless, and goofy.

399
00:33:26,960 --> 00:33:28,560
I think you two would get along.

400
00:33:30,320 --> 00:33:31,720
I'm not so sure, Pun.

401
00:33:32,680 --> 00:33:36,120
Pie, don't be so biased.

402
00:33:37,080 --> 00:33:39,920
Look, I'm meeting him today.

403
00:33:40,680 --> 00:33:42,800
I'll pick him up, and we'll
have dinner with my parents.

404
00:33:43,480 --> 00:33:44,440
Come with me.

405
00:33:53,560 --> 00:33:55,680
<i>I won't be able to see you today.</i>

406
00:33:55,760 --> 00:33:57,880
<i>I have a bad headache.</i>
<i>Probably a hangover.</i>

407
00:33:57,960 --> 00:33:59,360
<i>Sorry about that.</i>

408
00:34:02,120 --> 00:34:03,840
Alright, let's play it cool.

409
00:34:06,720 --> 00:34:07,880
PUN

410
00:34:14,120 --> 00:34:15,120
Hello, Pun?

411
00:34:15,880 --> 00:34:17,760
I'll pick you up at around 4 p.m.

412
00:34:17,840 --> 00:34:19,560
We'll chill for a bit, then have dinner.

413
00:34:20,480 --> 00:34:23,440
Sorry, Pun. I was just about to text you.

414
00:34:25,080 --> 00:34:26,920
I need to reschedule for today.

415
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,040
<i>‪Well…</i>

416
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:31,040
I have a bad headache,
probably from drinking.

417
00:34:31,600 --> 00:34:33,360
I can barely stand. My head's spinning.

418
00:34:34,280 --> 00:34:37,159
With that kind of condition,
you need to come here right away.

419
00:34:37,239 --> 00:34:40,360
I'll have the housekeeper make congee
and get you hangover meds.

420
00:34:41,080 --> 00:34:43,400
It's fine, Pun. I'm managing.

421
00:34:44,040 --> 00:34:45,520
But…

422
00:34:45,600 --> 00:34:48,800
I don't want your mom and dad
to see me like this. It's not a good look.

423
00:34:49,400 --> 00:34:52,199
<i>I want to go in fresh,</i>
<i>looking like I've got it together.</i>

424
00:34:53,719 --> 00:34:55,239
Can we reschedule?

425
00:34:55,840 --> 00:34:58,040
Yeah, that's fine.

426
00:34:58,120 --> 00:34:59,240
But next time,
don't back out last minute.

427
00:34:59,880 --> 00:35:00,920
<i>Sorry again.</i>

428
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:04,040
Once I'm feeling better,
I'll reach out to you right away.

429
00:35:04,120 --> 00:35:05,560
Okay, rest up.

430
00:35:06,080 --> 00:35:07,800
Pun, about…

431
00:35:07,880 --> 00:35:09,520
You want to ask about my wife, right?

432
00:35:11,320 --> 00:35:12,520
<i>Yes.</i>

433
00:35:13,120 --> 00:35:14,520
Did she say anything?

434
00:35:18,280 --> 00:35:19,880
Pie was a bit shocked.

435
00:35:19,960 --> 00:35:21,560
But she's okay. She didn't say much.

436
00:35:21,640 --> 00:35:22,760
Don't worry about it.

437
00:35:22,840 --> 00:35:26,000
We'll meet again next time,
and I'll introduce you to her properly.

438
00:35:26,920 --> 00:35:27,880
<i>Okay.</i>

439
00:35:28,600 --> 00:35:30,560
Please tell her I'm sorry.

440
00:35:31,080 --> 00:35:32,720
Yeah, rest up.

441
00:36:12,800 --> 00:36:13,680
Pie.

442
00:36:14,280 --> 00:36:16,160
Koh isn't coming anymore.

443
00:36:16,240 --> 00:36:18,520
He drank a lot last night and is hungover.

444
00:36:19,560 --> 00:36:22,760
And he asked me
to apologize to you for scaring you.

445
00:36:26,600 --> 00:36:28,600
It's fine. I've already
forgotten about it.

446
00:36:31,600 --> 00:36:33,200
That's why you're so sweet.

447
00:36:34,080 --> 00:36:35,120
Quick to forget

448
00:36:36,280 --> 00:36:38,000
and easygoing.

449
00:36:38,080 --> 00:36:39,280
I like that about you.

450
00:37:39,240 --> 00:37:41,080
Let's end it here.

451
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:53,160
Let's not bind ourselves with a title.

452
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:56,280
I don't want you to struggle
because of me.

453
00:37:58,120 --> 00:37:59,600
I don't want to be selfish.

454
00:38:03,360 --> 00:38:04,680
We really can't go on.

455
00:38:06,040 --> 00:38:07,920
Are we really breaking up?

456
00:38:35,320 --> 00:38:38,040
Hello, Pie!

457
00:38:38,640 --> 00:38:41,080
Pie, I've got something good for you.

458
00:38:41,160 --> 00:38:42,840
Hurry up and come down.

459
00:39:03,760 --> 00:39:06,400
Here, Pie.

460
00:39:06,480 --> 00:39:09,360
Black chicken stew with Chinese herbs,
the recipe for fertility.

461
00:39:09,440 --> 00:39:11,680
Eat it, and you'll feel full of energy.

462
00:39:11,760 --> 00:39:13,360
You'll definitely have a baby soon!

463
00:39:14,080 --> 00:39:15,600
- Mom.
- Yes?

464
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:19,400
What's wrong, Pie? What happened?

465
00:39:19,480 --> 00:39:21,200
Wait a second.

466
00:39:22,040 --> 00:39:24,120
Is this about Pun's mom? Why?

467
00:39:24,200 --> 00:39:26,080
Did she come to pick a fight
with you again?

468
00:39:26,160 --> 00:39:27,440
- Tell me.
- No, Mom.

469
00:39:27,520 --> 00:39:29,160
It's not about her.

470
00:39:29,840 --> 00:39:31,360
I just wanted to tell you that…

471
00:39:31,440 --> 00:39:32,720
What?

472
00:39:32,800 --> 00:39:35,120
What is it, Pie? Just say it.

473
00:39:44,480 --> 00:39:46,440
I quit my job,
and I'm feeling kind of lonely.

474
00:39:47,200 --> 00:39:48,680
How about we go on a trip together?

475
00:39:49,840 --> 00:39:51,560
Oh, come on, sweetie.

476
00:39:51,640 --> 00:39:54,880
It's just that? Why are you hesitating?

477
00:39:56,200 --> 00:39:57,400
Yes.

478
00:39:57,480 --> 00:40:01,200
Come on. It's still hot. Hurry up and eat.

479
00:40:01,280 --> 00:40:04,360
You know, it'll help nourish your body.
I'll go get you some water.

480
00:40:30,920 --> 00:40:32,520
If you're interested in selling,

481
00:40:32,600 --> 00:40:35,480
my client will offer you a price
higher than the market value.

482
00:40:35,560 --> 00:40:37,000
Feel free to make any offer.

483
00:40:37,960 --> 00:40:39,800
What does your client want the house for?

484
00:40:39,880 --> 00:40:42,800
They're thinking of tearing it down
to build a new house or condo.

485
00:40:43,600 --> 00:40:44,840
I'm not selling.

486
00:40:44,920 --> 00:40:46,960
My client is offering a really good price.

487
00:40:47,560 --> 00:40:49,840
It's okay. I'm not
in any financial trouble.

488
00:40:57,200 --> 00:40:59,840
You want to renovate
great-grandma's house?

489
00:41:01,480 --> 00:41:02,680
You think you can handle it?

490
00:41:02,760 --> 00:41:04,960
Come on. I'm not doing it myself.

491
00:41:05,040 --> 00:41:06,760
I'll just hire someone.

492
00:41:06,840 --> 00:41:09,280
I want to turn great-grandma's house
into a cafe.

493
00:41:09,880 --> 00:41:12,560
Vintage cafes are trending right now.

494
00:41:12,640 --> 00:41:15,440
If we do it right, it could be
a popular spot for check-ins!

495
00:41:15,520 --> 00:41:19,000
Girl, don't you think that house
is too big to be a coffee shop?

496
00:41:19,600 --> 00:41:21,440
We can renovate it bit by bit.

497
00:41:21,520 --> 00:41:23,840
Once it's good, we can expand.

498
00:41:23,920 --> 00:41:26,400
Let me do it, please, Uncle Dech?

499
00:41:26,480 --> 00:41:28,040
Please.

500
00:41:28,120 --> 00:41:29,440
Please.

501
00:41:31,440 --> 00:41:33,440
Please, Uncle Dech.

502
00:41:33,520 --> 00:41:34,560
Please…

503
00:41:35,640 --> 00:41:36,720
Please.

504
00:41:38,120 --> 00:41:41,120
- Please, Uncle Dech.
- Alright.

505
00:41:41,920 --> 00:41:43,720
But there's a condition.

506
00:41:44,600 --> 00:41:45,920
What condition?

507
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:48,400
I'll let you open the cafe.

508
00:41:49,040 --> 00:41:52,280
But you have to help me with the museum.

509
00:41:53,560 --> 00:41:54,840
What museum?

510
00:42:01,400 --> 00:42:03,440
I'm going to open
a museum of ancient fabrics.

511
00:42:03,520 --> 00:42:06,080
Really? That's a big project!

512
00:42:06,680 --> 00:42:10,600
I know it'll be chaotic,
but I've wanted to do this for years.

513
00:42:10,680 --> 00:42:14,160
My family's collected ancient fabrics
since great grandma's time,

514
00:42:14,240 --> 00:42:15,440
all the way to my generation.

515
00:42:15,520 --> 00:42:17,880
There are so many valuable, old items.

516
00:42:17,960 --> 00:42:21,760
But keeping them all to myself
feels wrong.

517
00:42:21,840 --> 00:42:24,880
I want others to see
the beauty of these fabrics,

518
00:42:24,960 --> 00:42:27,440
to experience history through them.

519
00:42:28,240 --> 00:42:30,560
Wait, hold on.

520
00:42:30,640 --> 00:42:32,640
Did you get diagnosed
with something serious?

521
00:42:32,720 --> 00:42:35,560
- What are you talking about?
- Well.

522
00:42:35,640 --> 00:42:37,800
You're acting like you're
clearing out your assets

523
00:42:37,880 --> 00:42:41,000
to work on something for society
before leaving this world.

524
00:42:41,080 --> 00:42:43,240
Come on. Tell me.

525
00:42:43,840 --> 00:42:45,880
What's wrong? Cancer?

526
00:42:45,960 --> 00:42:48,400
Oh my God, stop that!
Knock on the table three times!

527
00:42:51,160 --> 00:42:53,760
No, I just want to get it done now
because I'm afraid

528
00:42:53,840 --> 00:42:56,280
that I won't be able to manage it
when I'm older.

529
00:42:57,440 --> 00:42:59,680
Also, Mink has already graduated, right?

530
00:42:59,760 --> 00:43:04,760
Our great-grandma's old, abandoned house
is due for renovation into a museum.

531
00:43:06,920 --> 00:43:09,600
Have you found someone
to help design and create the museum?

532
00:43:10,240 --> 00:43:12,480
Not yet. I'm still looking around.

533
00:43:13,680 --> 00:43:15,440
You don't need to look far.

534
00:43:15,520 --> 00:43:17,920
Just ask Pun, my son.

535
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:20,000
He's the expert when it comes to museums.

536
00:43:21,760 --> 00:43:23,560
If you're going to open a museum,

537
00:43:23,640 --> 00:43:25,840
my son should be the one to do it.

538
00:43:25,920 --> 00:43:28,440
And the important thing is,

539
00:43:28,520 --> 00:43:31,560
I hold major shares in Pun's company.
I'll take care of it.

540
00:43:31,640 --> 00:43:32,480
Go ahead.

541
00:43:32,560 --> 00:43:34,440
Okay.

542
00:43:34,960 --> 00:43:37,320
What are you talking about?
We can handle it!

543
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:44,480
The situation at our company
isn't good right now.

544
00:43:44,560 --> 00:43:46,880
There are only big projects,
and money's tied up.

545
00:43:46,960 --> 00:43:50,120
We need some smaller projects to come in,
so we can have some cash flow.

546
00:43:50,200 --> 00:43:52,040
Speaking of smaller projects,

547
00:43:52,120 --> 00:43:54,520
there's one from someone we know.

548
00:43:55,120 --> 00:43:58,040
- Who?
- Your mom.

549
00:43:58,120 --> 00:43:59,760
My mom's project?

550
00:43:59,840 --> 00:44:03,160
Yeah, she called me yesterday.

551
00:44:03,240 --> 00:44:05,920
She said one of her friends…

552
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:08,440
Mr. Dech, wants to open a museum.

553
00:44:08,520 --> 00:44:10,440
Uncle Dech, Mungmink's uncle.

554
00:44:10,520 --> 00:44:11,640
Really?

555
00:44:12,400 --> 00:44:13,360
Yes.

556
00:44:14,040 --> 00:44:15,440
Uncle Dech is Mungmink's uncle.

557
00:44:15,960 --> 00:44:17,280
He's also a friend of my mom.

558
00:44:19,280 --> 00:44:22,040
Got it. I've scheduled
a meeting with him tomorrow.

559
00:44:22,120 --> 00:44:25,920
If it's Mungmink's project,
I'm sure it's not a small or easy one.

560
00:44:27,040 --> 00:44:29,960
Come on. Let's not jump to conclusions.

561
00:44:30,040 --> 00:44:32,320
Maybe your friend has changed.

562
00:44:32,400 --> 00:44:35,720
I'll talk to him first,
then we'll see. Okay?

563
00:44:36,760 --> 00:44:38,200
The leaves are all burnt!

564
00:44:38,280 --> 00:44:41,760
I told you, from 9 a.m. to noon,
the monstera needs to be in the shade.

565
00:44:41,840 --> 00:44:43,120
Are you trying to kill my plants?

566
00:44:43,200 --> 00:44:45,040
I'm sorry, ma'am, I forgot.

567
00:44:45,120 --> 00:44:47,080
If you forget,
go get a pen and write it down.

568
00:44:47,160 --> 00:44:50,160
Make sure you note
that if this monstera dies,

569
00:44:50,240 --> 00:44:51,920
you'll have to leave this house.

570
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:53,160
Yes, ma'am.

571
00:44:53,240 --> 00:44:54,720
- Get a pen and write it down.
- Yes.

572
00:44:58,840 --> 00:45:00,920
Pun. Phu.

573
00:45:03,360 --> 00:45:04,520
Hello.

574
00:45:05,360 --> 00:45:06,800
What are you doing here?

575
00:45:16,600 --> 00:45:20,440
I want to open a fabric museum
because I've collected a lot of fabrics.

576
00:45:20,520 --> 00:45:23,200
I want to organize it properly.

577
00:45:23,280 --> 00:45:25,040
And for the rare fabrics,

578
00:45:25,120 --> 00:45:27,760
I want to share them
with the new generation to see.

579
00:45:28,360 --> 00:45:30,960
Your mom, Nhun, recommended you.

580
00:45:31,040 --> 00:45:32,840
She saw that you
are working in this field.

581
00:45:33,640 --> 00:45:34,680
Yes.

582
00:45:34,760 --> 00:45:38,120
Why didn't you tell me you scheduled
a meeting with Pun today?

583
00:45:38,200 --> 00:45:39,280
I just found out.

584
00:45:39,360 --> 00:45:40,920
Well, sweetie.

585
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:43,440
It doesn't matter when,
as long as you know now.

586
00:45:44,200 --> 00:45:46,120
Let's get back to work,
so we don't waste time.

587
00:45:46,200 --> 00:45:47,080
Alright.

588
00:45:47,160 --> 00:45:49,240
You can take a look at the work

589
00:45:49,320 --> 00:45:51,640
that my company has done
related to museums.

590
00:45:52,240 --> 00:45:53,480
Sure.

591
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:58,000
No need to look.
I already know the work will be great.

592
00:45:58,080 --> 00:45:59,840
Because I've interned there before.

593
00:45:59,920 --> 00:46:02,280
The one-day internship where you quit?

594
00:46:05,600 --> 00:46:08,080
I think it all looks a bit repetitive.

595
00:46:08,160 --> 00:46:11,000
I want something unique,
something that stands out.

596
00:46:12,280 --> 00:46:15,440
If that's the case, let's talk

597
00:46:15,520 --> 00:46:17,840
about what kind of uniqueness
you're looking for.

598
00:46:17,920 --> 00:46:19,640
Next time, we can present a proposal.

599
00:46:20,480 --> 00:46:23,120
Then let me explain the background first.

600
00:46:23,200 --> 00:46:26,200
We have a family house.
It's my great-grandma's house.

601
00:46:26,880 --> 00:46:28,960
At first, I just wanted to open a cafe.

602
00:46:29,040 --> 00:46:31,400
But he wants to turn it
into a fabric museum as well.

603
00:46:31,480 --> 00:46:33,640
We've decided to do both,

604
00:46:33,720 --> 00:46:36,360
a museum and a cafe in the same space.

605
00:46:36,960 --> 00:46:38,080
Alright.

606
00:46:38,160 --> 00:46:42,920
Well, for the fabric museum,
do you have anyone helping with it?

607
00:46:44,760 --> 00:46:46,720
No, I'm handling it myself.

608
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:50,120
Well, hold on a second.

609
00:46:50,200 --> 00:46:54,160
Before we start, let me ask you.

610
00:46:54,240 --> 00:46:57,680
How much do you know about fabrics
if we're creating a fabric museum?

611
00:46:58,840 --> 00:47:02,280
Your mom knows,
but I've never talked to you about it.

612
00:47:03,480 --> 00:47:08,440
To be honest, Uncle Dech,
I don't know much about fabrics.

613
00:47:08,520 --> 00:47:12,000
But at our company,
we have experts who specialize in fabrics.

614
00:47:12,600 --> 00:47:14,240
They'll help manage

615
00:47:14,320 --> 00:47:17,600
the fabric-related work
and gather accurate information.

616
00:47:17,680 --> 00:47:21,120
And more importantly, they'll help
create content for the fabric museum.

617
00:47:21,200 --> 00:47:23,160
Bring them over and let's talk.

618
00:47:23,240 --> 00:47:25,280
If we're on the same page,
we can start right away.

619
00:47:25,360 --> 00:47:27,640
I don't want to keep
talking about it. I'm lazy.

620
00:47:28,240 --> 00:47:31,560
Sounds good.
When should we set the meeting?

621
00:47:31,640 --> 00:47:33,480
- Tomorrow.
- Tomorrow?

622
00:47:36,400 --> 00:47:37,760
Got it. Tomorrow it is.

623
00:47:43,760 --> 00:47:45,560
You want me to meet the client tomorrow?

624
00:47:45,640 --> 00:47:46,600
Yes.

625
00:47:47,200 --> 00:47:49,560
Pun, you're contradicting yourself.

626
00:47:49,640 --> 00:47:53,320
At first, you had me quit university
to prepare for having a baby,

627
00:47:53,400 --> 00:47:55,960
and now you're asking me
to help with the company.

628
00:47:56,880 --> 00:47:59,120
It's not fair. I'm not doing it.

629
00:47:59,800 --> 00:48:02,760
Wait, Pie. Look.

630
00:48:04,200 --> 00:48:05,920
Don't reject it just yet.

631
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:07,400
Check out the client's background first.

632
00:48:08,200 --> 00:48:09,480
I think you'll change your mind.

633
00:48:16,680 --> 00:48:17,560
Here.

634
00:48:17,640 --> 00:48:20,960
MR. DECHNARONG SORINEE

635
00:48:21,040 --> 00:48:22,480
Mr. Dechnarong.

636
00:48:23,920 --> 00:48:26,080
You mom's close friend, Mink's uncle.

637
00:48:26,160 --> 00:48:27,120
Yes.

638
00:48:27,960 --> 00:48:31,160
I want you to take this job
because I'm sure Uncle Dech will like you.

639
00:48:31,920 --> 00:48:34,080
And if you do this, it'll make my mom--

640
00:48:34,160 --> 00:48:35,480
Like me too.

641
00:48:38,480 --> 00:48:41,600
You're saying your mom doesn't like me,

642
00:48:42,880 --> 00:48:43,920
right?

643
00:48:45,440 --> 00:48:46,360
Pie.

644
00:48:46,960 --> 00:48:48,520
That's not it.

645
00:48:49,440 --> 00:48:51,280
It's not that my mom doesn't like you.

646
00:48:51,880 --> 00:48:54,280
She just doesn't understand
certain things.

647
00:48:55,080 --> 00:48:56,720
The point is, if you take this job,

648
00:48:57,720 --> 00:49:00,120
it will improve things at home.

649
00:49:06,960 --> 00:49:09,920
And as for the baby,
we'll stick with the original plan.

650
00:49:10,760 --> 00:49:14,080
I'm asking you to do this
because it's our own project.

651
00:49:14,160 --> 00:49:16,000
But once you're pregnant,

652
00:49:16,080 --> 00:49:19,080
we'll stop and find someone else to help.

653
00:49:19,680 --> 00:49:22,560
But teaching work, you can't just stop.

654
00:49:23,760 --> 00:49:26,120
I don't want you teaching
while pregnant until you give birth.

655
00:49:27,280 --> 00:49:28,440
It's not the same thing.

656
00:49:37,480 --> 00:49:39,080
If you don't want to do this,

657
00:49:40,200 --> 00:49:42,120
if you don't want to look
at Uncle Dech's fabrics,

658
00:49:43,800 --> 00:49:44,840
then you don't have to.

659
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:51,480
We can just focus on having the baby.

660
00:49:52,720 --> 00:49:53,560
I won't force you.

661
00:49:58,320 --> 00:49:59,720
Pun.

662
00:50:01,280 --> 00:50:03,440
I haven't rejected it yet.

663
00:50:10,240 --> 00:50:12,080
Then…

664
00:50:13,880 --> 00:50:15,760
Please do it. Okay?

665
00:50:16,960 --> 00:50:18,640
Please. Look.

666
00:50:19,240 --> 00:50:20,480
Take a look at his fabrics.

667
00:50:20,560 --> 00:50:21,440
Please.

668
00:50:23,080 --> 00:50:24,640
Alright?

669
00:50:26,040 --> 00:50:27,360
Just take a look.

670
00:50:28,120 --> 00:50:29,200
…PRESERVE THEM
AS THAILAND'S NATIONAL TREASURE

671
00:50:29,280 --> 00:50:30,640
Please.

672
00:50:31,400 --> 00:50:34,080
- Please.
- Okay.

673
00:50:35,040 --> 00:50:36,760
I'll do it, Pun.

674
00:50:41,840 --> 00:50:43,040
You're the sweetest.

675
00:50:45,360 --> 00:50:47,240
The sweetest ever.

676
00:50:47,320 --> 00:50:48,680
- You're the sweetest.
- Okay.

677
00:50:48,760 --> 00:50:50,280
- Alright, Pun.
- Pie.

678
00:50:50,360 --> 00:50:52,720
- Pun! Pun.
- The sweetest.

679
00:50:53,440 --> 00:50:54,840
I give in.

680
00:50:59,040 --> 00:51:00,080
You're the sweetest.

681
00:51:10,080 --> 00:51:13,160
Do you know which fabric expert
Pun is bringing to help my uncle?

682
00:51:13,880 --> 00:51:15,560
- No, I don't.
- Don't lie.

683
00:51:16,360 --> 00:51:17,600
Is it Pie?

684
00:51:17,680 --> 00:51:19,280
I don't know.

685
00:51:19,360 --> 00:51:21,760
I don't know, I swear.

686
00:51:22,400 --> 00:51:26,400
Fine. But if it is Pie, tell Pun

687
00:51:26,480 --> 00:51:29,440
that his wife can't handle my uncle.
I'm telling you.

688
00:51:29,520 --> 00:51:31,320
Do you still have a problem with Pie?

689
00:51:33,080 --> 00:51:35,120
Don't tell me you still like Pun.

690
00:51:39,120 --> 00:51:41,080
I've come a long way.

691
00:51:41,160 --> 00:51:44,240
I barely have time
to keep up with my dating schedule.

692
00:51:44,320 --> 00:51:45,600
What would I want with Pun?

693
00:51:47,160 --> 00:51:50,160
Someone like me
doesn't do anything immoral.

694
00:51:50,240 --> 00:51:52,680
Then why won't you go for Pie?

695
00:51:53,760 --> 00:51:55,480
I'm grown up enough to understand.

696
00:51:55,560 --> 00:51:57,320
Work is work, personal is personal.

697
00:51:57,400 --> 00:51:59,480
I need someone professional,

698
00:51:59,560 --> 00:52:01,640
someone who can handle the job
and get results.

699
00:52:01,720 --> 00:52:02,960
I may hate her guts,

700
00:52:03,040 --> 00:52:05,360
but if the work is good, I'm fine with it.

701
00:52:05,440 --> 00:52:08,160
But if it's not impressive, I'm out.

702
00:52:08,240 --> 00:52:11,760
And with Pie, I'm telling you,
she can't handle it.

703
00:52:37,320 --> 00:52:38,560
What are you looking at?

704
00:52:40,440 --> 00:52:41,760
I'm looking at the fabric.

705
00:52:42,880 --> 00:52:44,360
It's so beautiful.

706
00:52:45,400 --> 00:52:47,400
Your boss has great taste.

707
00:52:48,600 --> 00:52:50,520
It's just scraps of cloth in a frame.

708
00:52:50,600 --> 00:52:51,760
There's nothing special about it.

709
00:52:52,360 --> 00:52:54,360
This isn't just scraps of cloth.

710
00:52:54,440 --> 00:52:56,520
It's a Hmong baby-carrying cloth.

711
00:52:57,880 --> 00:53:00,320
It's a fabric that mothers or grandmothers

712
00:53:00,400 --> 00:53:03,880
weave and embroider to prepare
for the child that's about to be born.

713
00:53:04,480 --> 00:53:07,600
What I mean when I say
your boss has great taste

714
00:53:07,680 --> 00:53:10,640
is not only is this fabric
beautifully patterned,

715
00:53:10,720 --> 00:53:14,400
but it also reflects
how much he values family love.

716
00:53:14,480 --> 00:53:18,160
That's why it's framed and placed here.

717
00:53:18,240 --> 00:53:19,960
I'm really impressed.

718
00:53:21,840 --> 00:53:24,240
I've heard Nhun talk about you
for a long time.

719
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:27,200
But this is the first time
we've talked in person.

720
00:53:37,600 --> 00:53:38,680
Mr. Dechnarong.

721
00:53:38,760 --> 00:53:40,240
Hello.

722
00:53:41,320 --> 00:53:44,160
Hello. Nice to meet you.

723
00:53:45,040 --> 00:53:46,040
Yes.

724
00:53:51,920 --> 00:53:54,400
I once did my thesis in Mae Hong Son,

725
00:53:54,480 --> 00:53:57,160
so I studied the weaving traditions
of different ethnic groups.

726
00:53:57,240 --> 00:53:58,520
I see.

727
00:53:59,600 --> 00:54:03,040
It must not have been easy for you
to get this piece of fabric, right?

728
00:54:03,120 --> 00:54:06,200
Because each baby-carrying cloth

729
00:54:06,280 --> 00:54:09,480
is a masterpiece created with great effort
by the women in each family.

730
00:54:09,560 --> 00:54:10,480
They wouldn't give it away easily.

731
00:54:10,560 --> 00:54:13,520
Exactly. I had to keep pushing
for a long time to get it.

732
00:54:13,600 --> 00:54:15,200
I had to invest time
staying in Chiang Mai.

733
00:54:15,280 --> 00:54:17,880
Flying and traveling were exhausting.

734
00:54:17,960 --> 00:54:20,720
But it was definitely worth it.

735
00:54:20,800 --> 00:54:24,000
The fabric is beautiful
and hasn't faded from the light.

736
00:54:24,600 --> 00:54:27,520
That means you must rotate
other pieces in and out to display, right?

737
00:54:28,120 --> 00:54:30,480
Oh my, you knew that?

738
00:54:30,560 --> 00:54:32,920
I've been hanging
this fabric up for months,

739
00:54:33,000 --> 00:54:34,760
and no one's ever mentioned it.

740
00:54:34,840 --> 00:54:36,400
You're the first one to point it out.

741
00:54:36,480 --> 00:54:39,640
I'm just doing
what a fabric lover would do.

742
00:54:40,560 --> 00:54:42,560
You take really good care
of your fabrics, Mister.

743
00:54:43,600 --> 00:54:44,720
Don't be so formal.

744
00:54:44,800 --> 00:54:46,320
Just call me Uncle Dech.

745
00:54:46,400 --> 00:54:47,880
We both love fabrics.

746
00:54:48,480 --> 00:54:50,160
- Yes.
- Hey.

747
00:54:50,840 --> 00:54:52,160
- You know?
- Yes?

748
00:54:52,240 --> 00:54:54,200
I have even better fabrics
in my collection.

749
00:54:55,240 --> 00:54:56,200
Uncle!

750
00:54:57,560 --> 00:54:59,080
Pun and Phu are waiting.

751
00:55:00,360 --> 00:55:01,320
It's okay.

752
00:55:02,160 --> 00:55:03,800
- We can wait.
- Yeah.

753
00:55:03,880 --> 00:55:06,720
Take your time.
If you want to see more, feel free.

754
00:55:09,040 --> 00:55:11,920
Well, if it's not too much trouble,
I'd love to take a look.

755
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:13,040
Of course!

756
00:55:20,640 --> 00:55:22,120
Here it is.

757
00:55:22,840 --> 00:55:24,280
- And here too.
- It's so beautiful.

758
00:55:24,360 --> 00:55:26,320
Oh no! Mink!

759
00:55:26,400 --> 00:55:27,360
Close the curtains!

760
00:55:27,960 --> 00:55:28,880
Oh my goodness!

761
00:55:28,960 --> 00:55:32,320
Don't you know
that light is harmful to fabric?

762
00:55:32,400 --> 00:55:33,200
Close it tightly!

763
00:55:34,560 --> 00:55:35,440
Okay.

764
00:55:37,720 --> 00:55:40,440
Pie, do you know this?

765
00:55:42,880 --> 00:55:43,960
Yes.

766
00:55:44,720 --> 00:55:47,360
Ancient fabrics, if exposed
to too much light or heat,

767
00:55:47,440 --> 00:55:49,680
will deteriorate faster.

768
00:55:49,760 --> 00:55:51,440
The fabric's color changes,

769
00:55:52,040 --> 00:55:55,800
whether it's from light bulbs or sunlight.

770
00:55:55,880 --> 00:55:56,920
Well done.

771
00:55:57,600 --> 00:55:58,640
Thank you.

772
00:56:06,280 --> 00:56:09,680
This one, I really love it.

773
00:56:10,320 --> 00:56:12,280
Do you know what kind of fabric this is?

774
00:56:33,840 --> 00:56:34,960
The Muang Nakhon brocade.

775
00:56:36,320 --> 00:56:39,640
A woven fabric from Nakhon Si Thammarat,
passed down through the ages.

776
00:56:39,720 --> 00:56:41,240
Oh my!

777
00:56:41,880 --> 00:56:43,000
You're amazing.

778
00:56:43,080 --> 00:56:46,040
This fabric is a gold-threaded fabric
in the Sangwian style.

779
00:56:46,120 --> 00:56:49,080
It's a gold-threaded fabric
with the most complex design.

780
00:56:49,160 --> 00:56:53,040
It has a central pattern,
called Gaan Yeang Dok Si Kleeb.

781
00:56:53,120 --> 00:56:56,360
The body of the fabric
is surrounded by small patterns,

782
00:56:56,440 --> 00:56:57,680
called Chor Tang Tong.

783
00:56:57,760 --> 00:56:59,440
The edges of the fabric

784
00:57:00,080 --> 00:57:03,520
have bands running along,
featuring the Mae Laya Bup pattern,

785
00:57:03,600 --> 00:57:05,000
known as the Sangwian band.

786
00:57:05,080 --> 00:57:07,240
At the bottom of the fabric,
between the Sangwian bands,

787
00:57:07,320 --> 00:57:09,720
there are layers of conical patterns
stacked on top of each other.

788
00:57:09,800 --> 00:57:14,040
This is the highest level of woven fabric
used in the Siamese royal court.

789
00:57:15,880 --> 00:57:17,040
You're really impressive!

790
00:57:18,200 --> 00:57:21,080
Let's look over here.
I've got even more ancient fabrics!

791
00:57:21,160 --> 00:57:22,880
Oh my, this area isn't old enough.

792
00:57:22,960 --> 00:57:25,320
- Come this way. Follow me!
- Okay.

793
00:57:25,400 --> 00:57:28,600
Here, this way. Look.

794
00:57:32,360 --> 00:57:35,400
They have been with my great-grandma
since she was young.

795
00:57:35,480 --> 00:57:36,360
So beautiful!

796
00:57:47,440 --> 00:57:49,840
<i>This project is a bit rushed,</i>
<i>since it's an additional task.</i>

797
00:57:49,920 --> 00:57:51,640
<i>I'm going to introduce you to my brother.</i>

798
00:57:51,720 --> 00:57:53,440
<i>His name's Koh.</i>

799
00:57:54,840 --> 00:57:56,640
If you want me to do this,

800
00:57:57,240 --> 00:57:58,920
the designer needs to be someone else.

801
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:01,920
In all the time I've known you,
I've never asked you for anything.

802
00:58:02,000 --> 00:58:03,600
<i>This is the first time.</i>

803
00:58:03,680 --> 00:58:05,240
Who do you care about more?

804
00:58:05,320 --> 00:58:08,720
Your brother or your ex?
You need to choose.

805
00:58:08,800 --> 00:58:10,600
If Win agrees to take this job…

806
00:58:11,160 --> 00:58:12,320
…I'm stepping away.

807
00:58:12,400 --> 00:58:14,240
Don't use that tone with me.

808
00:58:14,760 --> 00:58:16,880
If I knew we'd meet again,
I wouldn't have married Pun.

809
00:58:16,960 --> 00:58:18,720
How about I apologize and get lost?

810
00:58:18,800 --> 00:58:20,680
After all these years,
can't you figure it out?

811
00:58:21,280 --> 00:58:23,920
<i>You couldn't figure it out back then,</i>
<i>and you still can't now?</i>

812
00:58:49,760 --> 00:58:54,440
Subtitle translation by:
Chomchanach Yanaharn
